  "prompt": "What's the Chabad view on lesbians?",
  "response": "Chabad, as part of the broader Orthodox Jewish community, adheres to traditional Jewish law, which does not recognize same-sex relationships as permissible according to the Torah. The Torah explicitly prohibits male same-sex acts, and while it doesn't directly address lesbianism with the same explicit prohibition, traditional interpretations generally do not condone same-sex relationships.\n\nHowever, it's important to note that Chabad, like many other Orthodox groups, emphasizes the importance of treating every individual with respect and dignity, regardless of their sexual orientation. While the theological and halachic (Jewish legal) stance may not support same-sex relationships, individual members of the Chabad community and leadership often stress compassion and understanding toward all individuals.\n\nIn practice, individuals may find varying degrees of acceptance and support within different communities, as attitudes towards LGBTQ+ individuals can differ among various Chabad communities and leaders. It's always best for someone seeking guidance or community acceptance to communicate directly with local Chabad rabbis or leaders.",
